  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset underpins a landmark study on closed-loop ultrasonic brain-machine interfaces and has been directly reused in two downstream scholarly contexts, including a publication in <em>Nature Neuroscience</em>, signaling meaningful scientific uptake despite the absence of broader citation or social media metrics.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Deposited in 2022 on CaltechDATA under an open-access green license, this dataset accompanies research into decoding motor plans using functional ultrasound neuroimaging as the sensing modality for a closed-loop brain-machine interface. The work represents an unusual convergence of ultrasonic sensing technology, real-time neural decoding, and human-computer interaction\u2014fields that have historically relied on electrophysiological methods rather than hemodynamic ultrasound imaging. The dataset is the product of a notably international collaboration spanning institutions in the United States and France, including the California Institute of Technology, UCLA Health, the University of Southern California, ESPCI Paris, CNRS, and Inserm, among others.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset's most concrete evidence of impact is its direct linkage to two downstream scholarly works. It supplements a preprint posted in late 2022 and, more significantly, a peer-reviewed article published in <em>Nature Neuroscience</em>\u2014one of the highest-impact journals in the neurosciences. Additionally, dedicated analysis software archived on Zenodo explicitly requires this dataset, underscoring that the data are not merely supplementary but are an active, functional component of a reproducible research pipeline. This kind of formal machine-readable dependency between a dataset and its associated software is a strong indicator of genuine reuse intent.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The contributor team spans more than eight named researchers with persistent ORCID identifiers, facilitating long-term attribution and discoverability. The breadth of institutional affiliations\u2014crossing U.S. academic medical centers, engineering schools, and French national research agencies\u2014reflects the interdisciplinary effort required to develop a functional ultrasonic brain-machine interface. Whitney Griggs is listed as the corresponding and first author, providing a clear point of contact for researchers seeking to build on this work.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Formal download and view statistics currently stand at zero in the DataCite record, and no citation or social media engagement has been captured at the time of analysis. These figures most likely reflect indexing latency and the specialized nature of the audience rather than a lack of genuine use, particularly given the confirmed linkage to a <em>Nature Neuroscience</em> publication. As the field of functional ultrasound neuroimaging and non-invasive brain-machine interfaces continues to grow, this openly available dataset is well positioned to serve as a foundational resource for replication studies and methodological extensions.</p>",
